      "source": [
        "1] What is the difference between K-Means and Hierarchical Clustering?\n",
        "Provide a use case for each\n",
        "- K-Means Clustering\n",
        "\n",
        " - How it works: Partitions data into k clusters by minimizing the distance between points and their cluster centroids.\n",
        "\n",
        " - Pros: Fast, scalable, works well with large datasets.\n",
        "\n",
        " - Cons: Requires choosing k in advance, sensitive to outliers.\n",
        "\n",
        " - Use Case: Customer segmentation in marketing (e.g., grouping customers by purchasing behavior).\n",
        "\n",
        "Hierarchical Clustering\n",
        "\n",
        " - How it works: Builds a tree-like structure (dendrogram) by successively merging or splitting clusters.\n",
        "\n",
        " - Pros: No need to specify the number of clusters upfront, gives hierarchy of relationships.\n",
        "\n",
        " - Cons: Computationally expensive for large datasets, less scalable.\n",
        "\n",
        " - Use Case: Gene expression analysis in biology (e.g., clustering genes based on similarity patterns)."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "sMzG7HzahO48"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "2] Explain the purpose of the Silhouette Score in evaluating clustering\n",
        "algorithms.\n",
        "- The Silhouette Score is a metric used to evaluate how well data points are clustered. It measures both cohesion (how close a point is to other points in its own cluster) and separation (how far it is from points in the nearest different cluster).\n",
        "\n",
        "The score ranges from -1 to +1:\n",
        "\n",
        "A score close to +1 means the point is well matched to its own cluster and far from others (good clustering).\n",
        "\n",
        "A score around 0 means the point lies on the boundary between two clusters.\n",
        "\n",
        "A score close to -1 means the point is likely in the wrong cluster.\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "uerBm8O0hvFf"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "3] What are the core parameters of DBSCAN, and how do they influence the\n",
        "clustering process?\n",
        "- DBSCAN (Density-Based Spatial Clustering of Applications with Noise) has two core parameters that drive its clustering process:\n",
        "\n",
        "The first is ε (epsilon), which defines the radius of the neighborhood around a data point. It decides how close points need to be to each other to be considered part of the same cluster. A small ε may result in many small clusters or even mark most points as noise, while a large ε may merge distinct clusters into one.\n",
        "\n",
        "The second is MinPts (minimum points), which specifies the minimum number of points required within the ε-neighborhood for a point to be considered a core point. If a point has at least MinPts neighbors within radius ε, it becomes a core point and can expand a cluster. Border points (fewer neighbors but within reach of a core point) join clusters, while points that are neither core nor border are treated as noise.\n",
        "\n",
        "Together, these parameters control cluster density: ε sets the scale of neighborhoods, while MinPts defines what “dense enough” means. Tuning them properly is crucial for DBSCAN to detect meaningful clusters, especially in datasets with varying densities."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "WXMe-jsZh7CN"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "4] Why is feature scaling important when applying clustering algorithms like K-Means and DBSCAN?\n",
        "- Feature scaling is important in clustering because both K-Means and DBSCAN rely on distance measures (usually Euclidean distance) to group data points. If features are on very different scales, the feature with the larger range will dominate the distance calculation, leading to biased and misleading clusters.\n",
        "\n",
        "For example, in customer data, if income is measured in thousands and age in years, the income values could overshadow age when calculating distances, even if both features are equally important for clustering. Scaling methods like Standardization (z-score) or Min-Max normalization bring all features to a comparable scale so that each contributes fairly.\n",
        "\n",
        "In short, without scaling, clustering results can become distorted, while proper scaling ensures that the algorithm captures the true structure of the data."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "gukJt9NziHmh"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "5]  What is the Elbow Method in K-Means clustering and how does it help\n",
        "determine the optimal number of clusters?\n",
        "- The Elbow Method is a technique used to find the optimal number of clusters (k) in K-Means clustering. It works by running K-Means with different values of k and calculating the Within-Cluster Sum of Squares (WCSS), which measures how tightly the points are grouped within each cluster.\n",
        "\n",
        "As k increases, WCSS always decreases because adding more clusters reduces distances within clusters. However, after a certain point, the rate of improvement drops sharply — the WCSS curve bends like an “elbow”. This bend indicates the point where adding more clusters doesn’t significantly improve clustering quality.\n",
        "\n",
        "Thus, the elbow point is chosen as the optimal number of clusters, balancing between underfitting (too few clusters) and overfitting (too many clusters). For example, if the curve sharply bends at k=4, then 4 clusters likely represent the best structure in the data.\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "Fi_YdRvfiS4y"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "''' 6] Generate synthetic data using make_blobs(n_samples=300, centers=4),\n",
        "apply KMeans clustering, and visualize the results with cluster centers.\n",
        "'''\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "from sklearn.datasets import make_blobs\n",
        "from sklearn.cluster import KMeans\n",
        "\n",
        "# Generate synthetic data\n",
        "X, y = make_blobs(n_samples=300, centers=4, cluster_std=0.60, random_state=42)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Apply KMeans\n",
        "kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=4, random_state=42)\n",
        "y_kmeans = kmeans.fit_predict(X)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Plot clusters\n",
        "plt.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=y_kmeans, s=50, cmap='viridis')\n",
        "\n",
        "# Plot cluster centers\n",
        "centers = kmeans.cluster_centers_\n",
        "plt.scatter(centers[:, 0], centers[:, 1], c='red', s=200, alpha=0.75, marker='X')\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.title(\"K-Means Clustering with 4 Centers\")\n",
        "plt.show()\n"
      ],

        "'''7] Load the Wine dataset, apply StandardScaler , and then train a DBSCAN\n",
        "model. Print the number of clusters found (excluding noise).\n",
        "'''\n",
        "from sklearn.datasets import load_wine\n",
        "from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler\n",
        "from sklearn.cluster import DBSCAN\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "\n",
        "# Load dataset\n",
        "data = load_wine()\n",
        "X = data.data\n",
        "\n",
        "# Scale features\n",
        "scaler = StandardScaler()\n",
        "X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Train DBSCAN\n",
        "dbscan = DBSCAN(eps=1.5, min_samples=5)  # you can tune eps and min_samples\n",
        "labels = dbscan.fit_predict(X_scaled)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Count clusters (exclude noise = label -1)\n",
        "n_clusters = len(set(labels)) - (1 if -1 in labels else 0)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"Number of clusters found (excluding noise):\", n_clusters)\n"

        "''' 8] Generate moon-shaped synthetic data using\n",
        "make_moons(n_samples=200, noise=0.1), apply DBSCAN, and highlight the outliers in\n",

        "'''\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "from sklearn.datasets import make_moons\n",
        "from sklearn.cluster import DBSCAN\n",
        "\n",
        "# Generate moon-shaped synthetic data\n",
        "X, y = make_moons(n_samples=200, noise=0.1, random_state=42)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Apply DBSCAN\n",
        "dbscan = DBSCAN(eps=0.2, min_samples=5)\n",
        "labels = dbscan.fit_predict(X)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Identify core clusters and outliers\n",
        "outliers = labels == -1\n",
        "\n",
        "# Plot clusters\n",
        "plt.scatter(X[~outliers, 0], X[~outliers, 1], c=labels[~outliers], cmap=\"viridis\", s=50)\n",
        "plt.scatter(X[outliers, 0], X[outliers, 1], c=\"red\", s=50, marker=\"x\", label=\"Outliers\")\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.title(\"DBSCAN on Moon-shaped Data with Outliers Highlighted\")\n",
        "plt.legend()\n",

      "source": [
        "''' 9] Load the Wine dataset, reduce it to 2D using PCA, then apply\n",
        "Agglomerative Clustering and visualize the result in 2D with a scatter plot.\n",
        "'''\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "from sklearn.datasets import load_wine\n",
        "from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler\n",
        "from sklearn.decomposition import PCA\n",
        "from sklearn.cluster import AgglomerativeClustering\n",
        "\n",
        "# Load dataset\n",
        "data = load_wine()\n",
        "X = data.data\n",
        "\n",
        "# Scale features\n",
        "scaler = StandardScaler()\n",
        "X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Reduce to 2D using PCA\n",
        "pca = PCA(n_components=2)\n",
        "X_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_scaled)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Apply Agglomerative Clustering\n",
        "agg_clust = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=3)\n",
        "labels = agg_clust.fit_predict(X_pca)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Plot the result\n",
        "plt.scatter(X_pca[:, 0], X_pca[:, 1], c=labels, cmap='viridis', s=50)\n",
        "plt.title(\"Agglomerative Clustering on Wine Dataset (2D PCA)\")\n",
        "plt.xlabel(\"Principal Component 1\")\n",
        "plt.ylabel(\"Principal Component 2\")\n",
        "plt.show()\n"
      ],
